"# Chapter 3 — Algol — the block-structured tradition

Algol is a family of languages that mattered less for what programs
were written in it — relatively few, in the end — and more for the
ideas it introduced. Almost every modern programming language draws
from Algol in some form. Motoi Scheme's block structure, its lexical
scoping, and its parameter-passing conventions are Algol
inheritance, filtered through Scheme.

## Algol 58 and Algol 60

Algol (short for ALGOrithmic Language) came out of a series of
international meetings in the late 1950s. American and European
computer scientists were meeting to design a common algorithmic
language that would be independent of any one manufacturer.

Algol 58, first published in 1958, was a preliminary design. Algol
60, published in 1960 after further refinement, is the version that
mattered. It was the first major language to have:

- **Block structure**: procedures containing local variables, and
  procedures containing other procedures. Nested scope. This is why
  the concept of 'a block' exists in language design vocabulary.
- **Recursion**: procedures could call themselves. This was
  controversial at the time; Fortran didn't allow it.
- **Formal parameter passing** with two mechanisms: call-by-value
  (the parameter is a local variable initialized to the argument)
  and call-by-name (the parameter is textually substituted at each
  use, with the argument's expression re-evaluated each time — a
  strange and powerful feature).
- **Lexical scoping**: an inner block can see the variables of the
  enclosing block, but not vice versa. Scoping is determined by the
  text of the program, not by run-time call history.
- **Data types** with explicit declarations.

These are ordinary features today. In 1960 most of them were novel
enough that programmers had to be taught what they meant.

## BNF

The Algol 60 report used a new notation to define the syntax
formally: Backus normal form (later renamed Backus-Naur form, since
Peter Naur wrote much of the report). BNF is a grammar notation:

```
<statement> ::= <assignment> | <if-statement> | <block>
<assignment> ::= <variable> := <expression>
```

BNF was the first widely-used metalanguage for describing
programming-language syntax. Every language spec since then has
used BNF or a variant. When Motoi Scheme's syntax is described, the
notation is a descendant of BNF.

## What Algol got right

- **Formal syntax**: the BNF grammar meant compiler writers could
  read the spec and build compatible implementations.
- **Structured control flow**: if-then-else, while, for. No goto
  encouraged, though it was still there. This structured-programming
  idea would be sharpened later by Dijkstra.
- **Nested scope**: a discipline that made programs much easier to
  reason about locally.
- **Formal parameters**: passing arguments to procedures, formally
  described.

## What Algol got wrong (or missed)

- **Call-by-name was too clever**. Powerful, but confusing, and
  hard to implement efficiently. Most later languages dropped it in
  favor of just call-by-value with pointer/reference options.
- **Input/output was left out of the spec**. Because different
  machines had such different I/O, the committee couldn't agree.
  Each Algol implementation added its own I/O extensions, making
  Algol programs non-portable in practice.
- **Algol was too pure for its industrial audience**. Fortran had
  I/O baked in and was familiar. Algol required people to think
  differently, and many refused.

Algol never became commercially dominant in the US. In Europe and
academia it was widely used through the 1960s and 1970s.

## Algol 68

Algol 68 was a more ambitious redesign published in 1968. It added
records, unions, procedures as first-class values, and a
mathematically rigorous specification.

Some people loved it. Many found it too complex. It never had the
adoption Algol 60 had. But its ideas influenced Pascal, Modula-2,
Ada, and C.

## The Algol family

Algol was directly ancestral to:
- **Pascal** (Niklaus Wirth, 1970) — a simpler, teaching-oriented
  Algol descendant.
- **Modula-2** (Wirth, 1978) — Pascal plus modules.
- **Ada** (US Department of Defense, 1980) — a large defense-oriented
  language.
- **C** (Dennis Ritchie, 1972) — took some structural ideas from
  Algol, plus a lot from BCPL.

And through those, essentially every mainstream imperative language
of the modern era. Java, C#, JavaScript, Python, Ruby, C++ all have
Algol grandparents somewhere.

## What Scheme got from Algol

- **Lexical scoping**: Scheme was one of the first Lisps to be
  strictly lexically scoped, following Algol's model. Earlier Lisps
  used dynamic scoping (variable lookups walk the call stack, not
  the text). Lexical scoping is now standard.
- **Block structure**: Scheme's `let` creates blocks with local
  variables, exactly the Algol idea.
- **Recursion**: obvious in retrospect, but Algol was where it was
  formally normalized.
- **Formal syntax**: Scheme's grammar is described in BNF-style
  notation.

## A tiny example

Algol-style block structure and lexical scoping, in Motoi Scheme:

```
(define (main)
  (let ((total 0))
    (let ((price 10)
          (tax 0.08))
      (let ((cost (* price (+ 1 tax))))
        (set! total (+ total cost))))
    ;; here 'total' is visible but 'price', 'tax', 'cost' are not
    total))

(main)
;; => 10.8
```

Every `let` opens a new scope. Variables in an inner `let` are
invisible to outer code once the inner block ends. This is exactly
what Algol 60 formalized — the discipline that inner blocks nest
inside outer blocks and can see, but not disturb, the enclosing
variables.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Algol didn't dominate any market. Very few programs today are
written in it. But its ideas — block structure, lexical scoping,
formal grammar description, recursion — are so foundational to
modern language design that almost every language quietly uses them.

Some contributions to the field aren't measured in market share.
They're measured in what people can build on top. Algol is one of
those.")
